[normal]2. [bold]To what extent are the needs of different groups of passengers (e.g. people with disabilities, older people, young people) taken into account in determining the provision of public transport[bold] to isolated communities?[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]2.1. 
[normal]In Devon m
[normal]ost
[normal] bus 
[normal]services
[normal] are now low floor/ accessible.
[normal] C
[normal]onventional
[normal] bus 
[normal]services
[normal] are augmented by:
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]2.2. 
[normal]In Devon 27% of passenger journeys on supported bus s
[normal]ervices are to/ from work (Passenger Focus survey 2013). While 
[normal]it is difficult to provide
[normal] empirical evidence, it would appear safe to assume that there is low time-elasticity for people travelling to work (little ability to continue in work if times change
[normal] significantly)
[normal]. This compares to
[normal] essential access to other services 
[normal]- 
[normal]e.g.  
[normal]t
[normal]own centr
[normal]e
[normal] services, shopping, chemists, and other services people need to use
[normal] - which
[normal] can 
[normal]often 
[normal]be expected to be 
[normal]more 
[normal]flexible (high time-elasticity)
[normal] 
[normal]enabling these needs to be
[normal] broadly met 
[normal]within
[normal] wider service
[normal] time bands
[normal].   
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]2.3. 
[normal]It is often stated that the travel needs of young people are not well served by pre-booked 
[normal]Demand Responsive Transport (
[normal]DRT
[normal])
[normal] services – and are therefore better served by regular timetabled services as there is a high degree of “turn-up-and-go” in their travel patterns.
