[normal]made
[normal] up of 
[normal]many
[normal] different
[normal] employers (SMEs) in different 
[normal]locations
[normal]. 
[normal]Significant and established flows are therefore often difficult to find.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]3.3. 
[normal]It is difficult to provide for all the interchange needs of people living along a route, as many interchange opportunities can conflict
[normal]. And different interchange needs at e.g. a station from bus to train or vice versa, or in different direction
[normal]s
[normal], may not be compatible
[normal] – unless the vehicle waits at the station thereby increasing journey time 
[normal](
[normal]and inconvenience for other passengers
[normal])
[normal] and op
[normal]erating costs through less efficient vehicle utilisation
[normal]. As with many decisions on shaping the public transport network, the decision tends to favour “the greatest benefit for the greatest number” – which will mean that 
[normal]not all
[normal] needs 
[normal]can
[normal] be 
[normal]met.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]3.4. 
[normal]In 
[normal]meeting demands, m
[normal]uch depends on 
[normal]local
[normal] 
[normal]geography
[normal]. 
[normal]Therefore different service types and models fit different areas best, and a single service model is unlikely to meet all rural needs. 
[normal]Depending
[normal] on 
[normal]population
[normal], w
[normal]here there are few
[normal]er roads
[normal] there may tend to 
[normal]be a 
[normal]greater
[normal] 
[normal]concentration
[normal] of travel demand on a corridor, and a greater 
[normal]number
[normal] of people 
[normal]travelling
[normal] on a 
[normal]public
[normal] 
[normal]transport
[normal] route. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]3.5. 
[normal]Devon County Council (DCC) has operated 12 Fare car schemes – a taxi-bus DRT service -  across the county with very dif
[normal]ferent costs/ passenger resulting. 
[normal]DRT often has higher costs per 
[normal]passenger
[normal] than conventional bus 
[normal]services
[normal], and a
[normal]gain 
[normal]geography
[normal] 
[normal]is a key influence 
[normal]on 
[normal]whether
[normal] this is the case. 
[normal]There is not a continuum of reducing service levels and reducing costs from high
[normal] frequency buses to low frequency buses to DRT: when replacing low frequency buses with DRT costs may therefore rise
[normal]. Where DRT schemes have been introduced with reduced overall costs this tends to be as a result of losing significant passenger numbers on 
[normal]the change from timetabled to pre-booked services.
