[normal]4. [bold]How effectively do Community Transport services address the needs of passengers in isolated communities? How could Community Transport be improved?[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]4.1. 
[normal]Community Transport
[normal] (CT)
[normal] may be well placed to cater for the needs of isolated communities on grounds of cost and responsiveness to small scale local needs. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]4.2. 
[normal]The 
[normal]capacity
[normal] to expand community 
[normal]transport
[normal] 
[normal]services
[normal] 
[normal]depends
[normal] 
[normal]substantially 
[normal]on the volunteer base. Much has been said 
[normal]about reduc
[normal]ing
[normal] levels of volunteering 
[normal]in recent
[normal] 
[normal]decades
[normal], 
[normal]which
[normal] is seen to be a constraint on 
[normal]the 
[normal]ability of 
[normal]sector 
[normal]to 
[normal]operat
[normal]e
[normal] a 
[normal]greater
[normal] 
[normal]range
[normal] of 
[normal]services
[normal] or cater for the 
[normal]travel
[normal] needs of more people. 
[normal]The driving licence restrictions introduced in 1997 rega
[normal]rding category D1 also provide an increasing constraint to sourcing drivers for minibuses as time goes by. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]4.3. 
[normal]DCC has supported the Community Transport sector for more than 25 years, and sees its 
[normal]own 
[normal]role as 
[normal]supporting and 
[normal]working with the sector to ca
[normal]pacity-build the sector
[normal]. 
[normal]Maintaining 
[normal]grant support to our CT can also help 
[normal]groups 
[normal]lever in matched funding from other sources, helping the con
[normal]s
[normal]ta
[normal]n
[normal]t challenge for the s
[normal]e
