[normal]5. [bold]To what extent should passengers in isolated communities be expected to rely on taxis and other demand-responsive transport services?[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]5.1. 
[normal]The passenger’s need and 
[normal]priority
[normal] is 
[normal]an
[normal] 
[normal]available
[normal], reliable, 
[normal]affordable
[normal] 
[normal]service
[normal], irrespective of how this is 
[normal]provided
[normal]. There is no reason to assume this 
[normal]should
[normal] be by 
[normal]a
[normal]ny 
[normal]particular
[normal] mode. 
[normal]From the viewpoint of the funding local authority, provided the appropriate service standards are met, the aim is to achieve best value. The mode wi
[normal]ll therefore be determined by circumstances, not from any inherent bias towards any one particularly mode.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]5.2. 
[normal]In rural areas t
[normal]axis 
[normal]cannot be regarded as 
[normal]more or less universally available
[normal]; in some market towns, let alone villages, there are still no acc
[normal]essible taxis available at all for those that need their more specialist support; where they are available 
[normal]the cost is 
[normal]clearly
[normal] 
[normal]prohibitive
[normal] for 
[normal]regular
[normal] use for many people. 
[normal]Joseph Rowntree Foundation (2010) identified that Transport 
[normal]P
[normal]overty is a greater fac
[normal]tor in rural areas than Fuel Poverty
[normal]: nationally 
[normal]we hear much about
[normal] the latter whilst
[normal],
[normal] e
[normal]ven now
[normal],
[normal] 
[normal]the importance of Transport Poverty 
[normal]is not 
[normal]widely
[normal] 
[normal]recognised
[normal].
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]5.3. 
[normal]D
[normal]RT s
[normal]ervices
[normal] are 
[normal]often
[normal] 
[normal]unsuitable
[normal] for 
[normal]regular
[normal] 
[normal]commuting
[normal] to work. 
[normal]For understandable reasons including juggling balance the need to meet diverse demands, 
[normal]schemes 
[normal]often 
[normal]only allow for booking up to a week/ fortnight ahead, which in itself is a barrier to meeting workers’ travel needs.
[normal] 
[normal]Therefore 
[normal]DRT
[normal], when it is cost-effect
[normal]ive, 
[normal]is 
[normal]likely
[normal] to 
[normal]work
[normal] better
[normal] for off-peak 
[normal]accessibility
[normal] needs to 
[normal]shopping
[normal]/ 
[normal]town
[normal] 
[normal]centre
[normal] 
[normal]facilities
[normal] and 
[normal]services
[normal].
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]5.4. 
[normal]Off
[normal]-
[normal]peak rural services in Devon tend to be more cost
[normal]-
[normal]effectively operated
[normal], on the margin,
[normal] by buses that are fully used in the peak for c
[normal]ommuting etc., rather than those buses being parked in the off-peak and using 
[normal]additional 
[normal]other smaller vehicles for off-peak DRT services.
