[normal]6. [bold]What are the main challenges associated with funding transport services in isolated communities? How can these s[bold]ervices be made more affordable?[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]6.
[normal]1. Relative Cost
[normal]The 
[normal]overriding 
[normal]challenge
[normal] 
[normal]is
[normal] the 
[normal]unchangeable
[normal] 
[normal]defining
[normal] feature of 
[normal]isolated
[normal] 
[normal]rural 
[normal]communities
[normal]: low 
[normal]population
[normal] and long 
[normal]distances
[normal] from centres that provide essential services and employment. 
[normal]Transport will therefore 
[normal]always be expensive to provide in terms of cost per passenger; this is inescapable, and the main challenge 
[normal]will the
[normal]re
[normal]fore
[normal] always be funding, and what is deemed worth funding. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Rural high cost/ passenger services will always compet
[normal]e unfavourably for shrinking council funding with lower cost/ passenger urban and inter-urban services. Cost/ passenger is a prime assessment tool, as applying it to decisions on service cuts provides the means of minimising the number of people affected b
[normal]y service reductions. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]6.
[normal]2. 
[normal]Network
[normal] 
[normal]Efficiency
[normal]Devon County Council has reduced the amount needed to support the local bus network through growing supported bus services to commercial operation and through working with operators of failing commercial serv
[normal]ices to make them fully commercial and financially sustainable in the long term. This reduction in funding that would otherwise be needed to continue to support the current network amounts to £2m annually, or 40% of the current bus support budget.
[normal] I.e. wit
[normal]hout growing these services the cost to the public purse of the current bus network would be 40% higher.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]But 
[normal]in spite of Devon’s success in 
[normal]growing network efficiency and effective management of the network in this way, and 
[normal]in achieving 
[normal]passenger growth i
[normal]n the last decade in contrast to
[normal] 
[normal]the national trend outside London, it has become clear that bus services which require a significant amount of funding support 
[normal]tend to be 
[normal]both 
[normal]difficult
[normal] to grow
[normal] and 
[normal]unlikely to ever become financially viable if funding supp
[normal]ort ended. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]6.3
[normal]. 
[normal]The “
[normal]m
[normal]yth of the empty bus”. 
[normal]In Devon all supported bus services use buses that are fully used in the peak hours. Using these buses in the off-peak will at times mean they are perhaps largely empty, but it is still more cost-effective to
[normal] provide rural services using these vehicles on the margin than to use other (additional) vehicles for lower demand off-peak travel, with the added costs that would bring. Many commercially viable bus services are also empty at times – to see a bus empty a
[normal]t times does not mean that resource is being wastefully used. Nevertheless this misperception may be in danger of distorting how society generally may value rural bus services as funding shortfalls result in increasing competition for dwindling funding res
[normal]ources across councils.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]6.4
[normal]. 
[normal]The 
[normal]Non-
[normal]Statutory
[normal] 
[normal]Nature
[normal] of 
[normal]Public
[normal] Transport 
[normal]Funding
[normal]The non-statutory nature of council bus service support relative to e.g. social care, school transport, and the need to maintain roads, means that no matter how sympathetic 
[normal]a council may be towards maintaining bus support, the size of the Spending Review funding cuts will inevitably mean that there will be little funding left for non-statutory services.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]6.
[normal]5. 
[normal]ENCTS Scheme Costs
[normal]In Devon the cost of the statutory English Natio
[normal]nal Concessionary Travel Scheme (ENCTS) is double that of the cost of supporting rural bus services. Whilst Devon sees the benefits of the scheme to eligible passholders, given the acute pressure on revenue budgets from the Spending Review, it has to be qu
[normal]estioned nationally whether it is sensible to continue to fund statutory free travel when this is at the expense of a reduced ability to travel through cuts to council funded routes.  
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]6.
[normal]6
[normal]. Cross-Sector Benefits 
[normal]A 
[normal]significant
[normal] 
[normal]element
[normal] of the 
[normal]value of bu
[normal]s 
[normal]services lies in other 
[normal]organisations
[normal] or in wider 
[normal]policy
[normal] aims
[normal], e.g.
[normal]:
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]It is difficult to 
[normal]fully 
[normal]engage with local public sector departments on this while government is not joined-up and does not provide joined
[normal]-up targets and messages on this to the local agencies. Agencies are not keen to work with the council to part-fund transport, even where this may reduce their overall net costs,  as their aims handed down from central government do not encourage this. 
[normal]As 
[normal]a result it is difficult for 
[normal]local government
[normal] to
[normal] successfully engage in joined-up service and budgetary planning with other public sector agencies when central government departments are not working together sufficiently on these issues
[normal].
[normal] 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]6.
[normal]7
[normal]. Long Term 
[normal]Benefits vs. Short Term Funding Needs
[normal]A significant element of the 
[normal]known significant 
[normal]benefits 
[normal]of public transport 
[normal]would also only be realised in the long term. 
[normal]T
[normal]he contribution of council public transport funding towards the 
[normal]economy, employment, youth oppo
[normal]rtunities is critical. Transport is a key component of action required to succeed on 
[normal]the Prevention Agenda 
[normal]– reducing de
[normal]pendence 
[normal]o
[normal]n
[normal] bene
[normal]f
[normal]it
[normal]s
[normal] through enabling employm
[normal]e
[normal]nt
[normal];
[normal] reducing dependence on 
[normal]bespoke care services through increased independen
[normal]ce in life
[normal] at
[normal] all ages; reducing ill-health through improving healthy lifestyles. 
[normal] 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The payback is long term, and budget cut targets need to be met this year or next. So no matter how much it would be sensible to continue to provide funding for public transport, as th
[normal]e payback is (a) often not within the council, and (b) not short-term or immediate, the
[normal]s
[normal]e 
[normal]immediate 
[normal]pressures are 
[normal]understandably 
[normal]greater than the long
[normal]-
[normal]term need to continue public transport funding.
[normal]   
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]6.8. Summary
[normal]To summarise, the 
[normal]significant 
[normal]cross-sect
[normal]or benefits that bus services provide
[normal],
[normal] across society and 
[normal]policy aims
[normal],
[normal] need to be reflected in national policies to enable these linkages to be made locally - by recognising the need to treat 
[normal]transport funding 
[normal]as wider than a purely 
[normal]transport budget
[normal] issue.
[normal] Only through such a new approach will 
[normal]the public sector achieve the benefits that will accrue and grow from continued public transport funding
[normal] and will it avoid increas
[normal]ing
[normal] future costs and problems that would result 
[normal]if this is not addressed urgently.
